<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="History">History</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Geesthacht&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: History">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<ul>
<li>Around 800: A church is documented.</li>
<li>1216: First documentary mention of the settlement as <i>Hachede</i>, then a part of <a href="/wiki/Duchy_of_Saxony" title="Duchy of Saxony">Saxony</a>.</li>
<li>A change in the course of the Elbe cuts the settlement into two: <a href="/wiki/Geest" title="Geest">Geest</a><i>hacht</i> and <a href="/wiki/Marschacht" title="Marschacht">Marschacht</a> (in today's <a href="/wiki/Lower_Saxony" title="Lower Saxony">Lower Saxony</a>).</li>
<li>1296: Geesthacht becomes part of the Durchy of <a href="/wiki/Saxe-Lauenburg" title="Saxe-Lauenburg">Saxe-Lauenburg</a>, partitioned from Saxony</li>
<li>1370: Duke <a href="/wiki/Eric_III_of_Saxe-Lauenburg" class="mw-redirect" title="Eric III of Saxe-Lauenburg">Eric III</a> pawns Geesthacht - as part of the <a href="/wiki/Herrschaft_(territory)" title="Herrschaft (territory)">Herrschaft</a> of <a href="/wiki/Bergedorf" title="Bergedorf">Bergedorf</a> - to <a href="/wiki/Free_City_of_L%C3%BCbeck" title="Free City of Lübeck">Lübeck</a></li>
<li>1401: Duke <a href="/wiki/Eric_IV_of_Saxe-Lauenburg" class="mw-redirect" title="Eric IV of Saxe-Lauenburg">Eric IV</a> retakes the pawned area with force</li>
<li>1420: Geesthacht is ceded as part of a condominium to the Hanseatic cities <a href="/wiki/Hamburg" title="Hamburg">Hamburg</a> and Lübeck by the <a href="/w/index.php?title=Peace_of_Perleberg&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Peace of Perleberg (page does not exist)">Peace of Perleberg</a>.</li>
<li>1811: Geesthacht is annexed to <a href="/wiki/First_French_Empire" title="First French Empire">France</a> as part of the <a href="/wiki/Bouches_de_l%27Elbe" class="mw-redirect" title="Bouches de l'Elbe">Bouches de l'Elbe</a> département</li>
<li>1813: The condominium is restored</li>
<li>1865/66: The Swedish chemist <a href="/wiki/Alfred_Nobel" title="Alfred Nobel">Alfred Nobel</a> establishes a <a href="/wiki/Glycerin" class="mw-redirect" title="Glycerin">glycerin</a> factory in Geesthacht (on Krümmel hill) and invents <a href="/wiki/Dynamite" title="Dynamite">dynamite</a>. Krümmel becomes the first dynamite factory in the world.</li>
<li>1868: Lübeck sells its share in the condominium to Hamburg, Geesthacht becomes a part Hamburg's state territory</li>
<li>1906: Opening of the <a href="/w/index.php?title=Bergedorf-Geesthachter_Railway&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Bergedorf-Geesthachter Railway (page does not exist)">Bergedorf-Geesthachter Railway</a>(BGE).</li>
<li>1918–1933: Geesthacht is a hotbed of radical leftist parties (<a href="/wiki/Independent_Social_Democratic_Party_of_Germany" title="Independent Social Democratic Party of Germany">USPD</a>, <a href="/wiki/Communist_Party_of_Germany" title="Communist Party of Germany">KPD</a> and <a href="/wiki/Socialist_Workers%27_Party_of_Germany" title="Socialist Workers' Party of Germany">SAPD</a>) and acquires the nickname <i>Little Moscow</i>.</li>
<li>1924: Granted <a href="/wiki/Town_privileges" title="Town privileges">town privileges</a> by the Hamburg state order of 2 January.</li>
<li>1928: Destruction of the historical town centre by a fire.</li>
<li>1937: In the context of the territorial reorganization of the State of Hamburg (<a href="/wiki/Greater_Hamburg_Act" title="Greater Hamburg Act">Greater Hamburg Act</a>), Geesthacht is transferred to the <a href="/wiki/Prussia" title="Prussia">Prussian</a> province of <a href="/wiki/Province_of_Schleswig-Holstein" title="Province of Schleswig-Holstein">Schleswig-Holstein</a>, there becoming part of the <a href="/wiki/Kreis_in_Prussia" class="mw-redirect" title="Kreis in Prussia">district</a> (<i>Kreis</i>) of <i>Duchy of Lauenburg</i>.</li>
<li>1953: Suspension of passenger service on the <a href="/w/index.php?title=Bergedorf-Geesthachter_Eisenbahn&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Bergedorf-Geesthachter Eisenbahn (page does not exist)">Bergedorf-Geesthachter Eisenbahn</a> (a railway line).</li>
</ul>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Economics_and_transportation">Economics and transportation</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Geesthacht&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4" title="Edit section: Economics and transportation">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>Geesthacht is a major energy and scientific research center. It has the <a href="/wiki/Kr%C3%BCmmel_Nuclear_Power_Plant" title="Krümmel Nuclear Power Plant">Krümmel Nuclear Power Plant</a> (closed 2011 after Fukushima - "Atomausstieg"), a <a href="/wiki/Boiling_water_nuclear_reactor" class="mw-redirect" title="Boiling water nuclear reactor">boiling water nuclear reactor</a> on the River Elbe, and a <a href="/wiki/Pumped_storage" class="mw-redirect" title="Pumped storage">pumped storage</a> hydroelectrical plant situated within a few hundreds metres of the nuclear power plant. It consists of an artificial lake 80m above the river, where the water is pumped up from, and storage for later use in generating electricity when demand is high.</p>

<li><a href="/wiki/Bundesautobahn_25" title="Bundesautobahn 25">Freeway 25</a> from Hamburg</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Bundesstra%C3%9Fe_5" title="Bundesstraße 5">Federal road B5</a> from <a href="/wiki/Hamburg" title="Hamburg">Hamburg</a> in the west to <a href="/wiki/Lauenburg/Elbe" class="mw-redirect" title="Lauenburg/Elbe">Lauenburg</a> in the east</li>
<li>Disused railway line to <a href="/wiki/Hamburg-Bergedorf" class="mw-redirect" title="Hamburg-Bergedorf">Hamburg-Bergedorf</a></li>
<li>River port on the Elbe, Elbe <a href="/wiki/Canal_lock" class="mw-redirect" title="Canal lock">locks</a></li>
<li>The nearest airport is at <a href="/wiki/Hamburg_Airport" title="Hamburg Airport">Hamburg-Fuhlsbüttel</a></li>
<li>The nearest sea harbour is the <a href="/wiki/Port_of_Hamburg" title="Port of Hamburg">Port of Hamburg</a></li>
</ul>
